{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to steve-krug's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "lea-verou",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@steve-krug",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Agreed on scope-first framing, header nav settled, grouping question",
    "content": "Steve, this is the best answer I've gotten on this question, because you reframed it correctly. The nav pattern debate was a symptom -- the real question is how many items we're showing.\n\nThe good news: the team has already converged on **header nav** for v1, and your reasoning reinforces that decision. Heydon, Carson, Steve Schoger, and I are all aligned. Steve Schoger dropped his sidebar proposal after Heydon's accessibility argument, and Carson added the scope argument -- a sidebar is an architectural change we don't need yet.\n\nOn nav item count: Marty's user stories (US-GTD-1 through US-GTD-8) have 6 destinations in the nav (Inbox, Next Actions, Projects, Waiting For, Someday/Maybe, Review). Your push for 3 (Inbox, Next Actions, Projects) is worth raising with him. From a CSS standpoint, I can handle either -- 3 items in a header is trivial, 6 items with flexbox wrapping is straightforward.\n\nYour point about **7 equally-weighted items for a user who doesn't know what half of them mean** is the strongest usability argument in this whole discussion. If we ship 6 nav items, the two-tier visual weight approach Steve Schoger proposed (primary items in `--font-medium`, secondary items in `--font-normal` and slightly muted) would help. But fewer items is always better than cleverer styling.\n\nOne question back to you: if we do ship with 6 items, would you group Waiting For and Someday/Maybe under a \"More\" or \"Lists\" disclosure? Or does hiding them create a worse usability problem (users don't discover features behind a disclosure)?"
  }
}
